1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,631
AI DevKit is an operating model for AI-centric software engineering.  It

2
00:00:05,700 --> 00:00:10,252
publishes standards and workflow templates for a model of development where AI

3
00:00:10,310 --> 00:00:15,325
agents do the bulk of execution work, and humans gate the highest-leverage

4
00:00:15,383 --> 00:00:16,219
decisions.

5
00:00:16,544 --> 00:00:21,827
It combines a documentation standard called Progressive Disclosure docs with

6
00:00:21,861 --> 00:00:25,937
a multi-model lifecycle that runs from work intake all the way through

7
00:00:25,995 --> 00:00:27,074
to release.  The

8
00:00:27,144 --> 00:00:29,303
key word here is AI-centric.

9
00:00:29,628 --> 00:00:34,504
Not AI-assisted, where humans do the engineering and AI helps along the

10
00:00:34,551 --> 00:00:34,934
way.

11
00:00:35,259 --> 00:00:39,102
And not AI-native, where you throw out repos and commits and start

12
00:00:39,148 --> 00:00:39,961
from scratch.

13
00:00:40,286 --> 00:00:42,875
AI-centric sits between these two.

14
00:00:43,479 --> 00:00:48,727
It takes the existing software development world — git, repos, pull requests,

15
00:00:48,901 --> 00:00:52,359
continuous integration — and reshapes it around AI execution, while keeping the

16
00:00:52,393 --> 00:00:53,763
human checkpoints that actually matter.

17
00:00:54,763 --> 00:00:56,052
Here's the lifecycle.

18
00:00:56,493 --> 00:01:00,463
Work comes in as a story, epic, bug, or feature.

19
00:01:00,707 --> 00:01:06,443
It flows through three phases: Plan, Implementation, and Release.  In

20
00:01:06,477 --> 00:01:09,194
the diagram you can see two large boxes.

21
00:01:09,519 --> 00:01:13,316
On the left is Plan, on the right is Implementation.

22
00:01:13,699 --> 00:01:16,822
In each phase, Model A sits at the centre.

23
00:01:17,449 --> 00:01:21,466
Model A is the AI running the workflow — it holds the

24
00:01:21,513 --> 00:01:24,102
procedure and works through it step by step.

25
00:01:24,729 --> 00:01:29,233
Around it are the resources it draws on: the human, Model B,

26
00:01:29,698 --> 00:01:34,818
the code, Progressive Disclosure docs, and testing tools.  Model

27
00:01:34,899 --> 00:01:38,626
B is a second AI from an independent training lineage.

28
00:01:39,067 --> 00:01:43,792
It's consulted at specific cross-verification points that the workflow defines.

29
00:01:44,396 --> 00:01:48,378
The subtitle at the top of the diagram says "any two from

30
00:01:48,425 --> 00:01:53,928
independent training lineages." We deliberately don't hardcode which providers to use.

31
00:01:54,369 --> 00:01:58,978
What matters is that the two models come from different training lineages.

32
00:01:59,489 --> 00:02:04,563
Single-model AI has a known failure mode: it's confidently wrong in ways

33
00:02:04,621 --> 00:02:08,278
invisible to itself, and asking the same model to review its own

34
00:02:08,325 --> 00:02:10,693
output rarely catches the error.  The

35
00:02:10,739 --> 00:02:12,760
Plan phase produces a spec.

36
00:02:13,201 --> 00:02:18,634
The Implementation phase produces a deliverable — code, tests, updated docs,

37
00:02:18,657 --> 00:02:19,714
and git changes.

38
00:02:19,749 --> 00:02:23,696
That deliverable passes through Release, which is a continuous integration gate plus

39
00:02:23,754 --> 00:02:24,764
human approval.

40
00:02:25,764 --> 00:02:29,166
Plan is the only phase where the human is centrally involved.

41
00:02:29,201 --> 00:02:32,776
It turns a work item into an approved spec.  Model

42
00:02:32,869 --> 00:02:35,656
A executes the spec-creation workflow.

43
00:02:35,714 --> 00:02:40,752
It reads the repo's Progressive Disclosure docs, scans the code, and drafts

44
00:02:40,787 --> 00:02:45,792
a spec with acceptance criteria, edge cases, approach decisions, and

45
00:02:45,850 --> 00:02:46,674
a test plan.

46
00:02:47,278 --> 00:02:52,932
The workflow includes an explicit cross-verification step: Model B independently

47
00:02:53,025 --> 00:02:55,440
restates each acceptance criterion.

48
00:02:55,881 --> 00:03:01,209
If the two models' restatements diverge, that criterion is ambiguous and

49
00:03:01,244 --> 00:03:05,029
gets surfaced to the human for reconciliation.  The

50
00:03:05,075 --> 00:03:08,802
phase ends when the human signs off the spec.  The

51
00:03:08,837 --> 00:03:11,101
spec itself is a short markdown file.

52
00:03:11,798 --> 00:03:16,941
It has a title, acceptance criteria written in Given-When-Then form, an edge

53
00:03:16,988 --> 00:03:22,282
cases section, approach decisions with rationale, a test case table,

54
00:03:22,491 --> 00:03:25,742
an out-of-scope list, and a verification plan.

55
00:03:26,183 --> 00:03:28,969
There are nine principles a good spec must satisfy.

56
00:03:29,410 --> 00:03:33,926
Every acceptance criterion must be executable — it maps to a runnable

57
00:03:33,961 --> 00:03:34,588
test.

58
00:03:35,192 --> 00:03:37,897
Every spec must be reviewable in under five minutes.

59
00:03:38,408 --> 00:03:41,693
Edge cases get their own section rather than being buried in the

60
00:03:41,740 --> 00:03:42,610
happy path.

61
00:03:43,214 --> 00:03:47,533
And approach decisions are made in the spec, not deferred to implementation.

62
00:03:48,136 --> 00:03:53,152
When the AI sees multiple reasonable approaches, it names them and

63
00:03:53,233 --> 00:03:55,741
picks one with a reason.  That

64
00:03:55,799 --> 00:03:57,123
last point is important.

65
00:03:57,506 --> 00:04:01,581
If you let the AI defer decisions to implementation, it makes them

66
00:04:01,627 --> 00:04:06,805
implicitly, often inconsistently, and you only discover the choice when you're reading

67
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:07,397
the code.

68
00:04:08,001 --> 00:04:12,134
Forcing decisions into the spec means the human reviews them before any

69
00:04:12,215 --> 00:04:13,272
code is written.

70
00:04:14,272 --> 00:04:18,196
Implementation turns an approved spec into a deliverable bundle.

71
00:04:18,579 --> 00:04:22,376
The human is available on demand for clarifications but is not in

72
00:04:22,422 --> 00:04:23,595
the inner loop.  The

73
00:04:23,653 --> 00:04:27,786
workflow runs test-driven development: Red, Green, Refactor.

74
00:04:28,169 --> 00:04:30,991
Here's the discipline that makes this work for AI.

75
00:04:31,502 --> 00:04:35,019
One model writes the failing tests.

76
00:04:35,403 --> 00:04:40,790
A second model from an independent training lineage writes the implementation.

77
00:04:41,393 --> 00:04:45,410
This separation of test author and implementer is the key.

78
00:04:45,793 --> 00:04:51,215
Without it, the same model writes both sides, and implementation assumptions

79
00:04:51,262 --> 00:04:53,247
get silently baked into the tests.

80
00:04:53,758 --> 00:04:57,682
The tests pass, but they're testing the model's assumptions rather than the

81
00:04:57,717 --> 00:04:59,656
spec's requirements.  After

82
00:04:59,714 --> 00:05:04,857
test-driven development completes, Model A updates the affected Progressive Disclosure docs

83
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:09,722
to reflect the new reality, and Model B cross-verifies the doc updates

84
00:05:09,768 --> 00:05:11,475
against the actual code changes.

85
00:05:11,916 --> 00:05:13,460
Then the spec is archived.

86
00:05:13,530 --> 00:05:16,676
It moves to an archive directory and is no longer part of

87
00:05:16,723 --> 00:05:18,604
the agent's operating surface.

88
00:05:19,416 --> 00:05:23,863
Progressive Disclosure docs carry everything an agent needs going forward.

89
00:05:24,467 --> 00:05:28,960
The archive exists only for human audits and retrospectives.  This

90
00:05:29,018 --> 00:05:30,898
is a deliberate design choice.

91
00:05:31,502 --> 00:05:34,161
Specs are in-flight artifacts.

92
00:05:34,857 --> 00:05:37,644
They exist to coordinate the work while it's happening.

93
00:05:38,457 --> 00:05:42,973
Once the work lands, the knowledge gets absorbed into the Progressive Disclosure

94
00:05:43,019 --> 00:05:45,631
docs — the permanent record.

95
00:05:46,015 --> 00:05:49,173
Future agents don't need to read old specs.

96
00:05:49,614 --> 00:05:51,982
They read Progressive Disclosure docs.

97
00:05:52,982 --> 00:05:57,742
Progressive Disclosure docs are the substrate the whole lifecycle runs on.

98
00:05:58,021 --> 00:06:03,512
They give every repository a consistent operating surface for AI agents.  There

99
00:06:03,547 --> 00:06:04,592
are three tiers.

100
00:06:04,836 --> 00:06:09,480
Level zero is a three-hundred to five-hundred token identity card.

101
00:06:09,863 --> 00:06:14,600
It tells the agent what this repo is, what stack it uses,

102
00:06:14,925 --> 00:06:16,214
who maintains it.

103
00:06:17,027 --> 00:06:20,870
Level one is eight fixed structured summary files.

104
00:06:21,253 --> 00:06:25,328
They answer eight questions every agent needs answered to work safely in

105
00:06:25,386 --> 00:06:26,454
any repository.

106
00:06:26,895 --> 00:06:31,574
Level two is on-demand deep dives, loaded only when level one isn't

107
00:06:31,621 --> 00:06:33,200
detailed enough.  The

108
00:06:33,258 --> 00:06:37,031
eight level-one files cover: How do I run this?

109
00:06:37,460 --> 00:06:38,680
How is this shaped?

110
00:06:39,272 --> 00:06:40,456
Where do I edit?

111
00:06:41,048 --> 00:06:42,615
How do we write code here?

112
00:06:43,207 --> 00:06:44,984
How do I perform this task?

113
00:06:45,425 --> 00:06:47,492
What contracts must I preserve?

114
00:06:47,921 --> 00:06:50,696
What will break if I touch it naively?

115
00:06:51,381 --> 00:06:55,410
And what trust boundaries must I respect?  These

116
00:06:55,445 --> 00:06:57,488
eight categories are deliberately fixed.

117
00:06:57,755 --> 00:07:02,794
Agents, tooling, prompts, and reviewers can rely on a consistent

118
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:05,348
structure across an entire organisation.

119
00:07:05,952 --> 00:07:10,700
Every repo looks the same to an agent, even though the repos

120
00:07:10,747 --> 00:07:14,102
themselves are completely different.  The

121
00:07:14,160 --> 00:07:17,434
workflows are part of Progressive Disclosure docs.

122
00:07:18,038 --> 00:07:23,401
Each adopting repo's workflows file carries the spec-creation, implementation,

123
00:07:23,727 --> 00:07:26,919
and docs-verification workflows.

124
00:07:28,034 --> 00:07:33,014
These are materialised from AI DevKit's canonical templates at bootstrap, with the

125
00:07:33,061 --> 00:07:37,228
repo's specific tooling, paths, and commands filled in.

126
00:07:37,832 --> 00:07:41,838
This is what Model A actually executes during Plan and Implementation.

127
00:07:42,838 --> 00:07:47,737
A natural question is: why does AI DevKit use copy-paste prompts instead

128
00:07:47,772 --> 00:07:51,534
of skills, slash commands, or plugins?  The

129
00:07:51,580 --> 00:07:55,772
answer comes down to portability and transparency.  Skills

130
00:07:55,830 --> 00:07:58,326
and slash commands are tool-specific.

131
00:07:58,767 --> 00:08:02,017
A Claude Code skill doesn't work in Cursor.

132
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:04,479
A Cursor command doesn't work in Codex.

133
00:08:04,804 --> 00:08:08,693
If AI DevKit shipped its workflows as skills, you'd need a different

134
00:08:08,728 --> 00:08:12,547
implementation for every tool, and you'd be locked into whichever tool you

135
00:08:12,617 --> 00:08:14,533
started with.  Prompts

136
00:08:14,614 --> 00:08:15,706
are universal.

137
00:08:15,984 --> 00:08:18,910
They work in any agent session that can read files.

138
00:08:19,421 --> 00:08:22,521
You paste the prompt, the prompt tells the agent to read the

139
00:08:22,567 --> 00:08:25,667
workflow from GitHub, and the agent executes it.

140
00:08:26,271 --> 00:08:31,263
The same prompt works in Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, Gemini, or any

141
00:08:31,333 --> 00:08:33,341
future tool that reads repo files.  There's

142
00:08:33,376 --> 00:08:35,013
also a transparency benefit.

143
00:08:35,454 --> 00:08:36,917
A prompt is visible text.

144
00:08:36,952 --> 00:08:39,483
You can read it, understand it, modify it.

145
00:08:39,924 --> 00:08:42,687
A skill is a black box — you invoke it and hope

146
00:08:42,722 --> 00:08:44,000
it does what you expect.

147
00:08:44,441 --> 00:08:49,712
When the workflow changes, you update the markdown file, and every prompt

148
00:08:49,758 --> 00:08:53,543
that references it picks up the change automatically.

149
00:08:53,822 --> 00:08:58,501
There's no deployment step, no version mismatch, no "which version of the

150
00:08:58,547 --> 00:09:00,230
skill is installed?"  If

151
00:09:00,288 --> 00:09:05,188
your tool supports custom commands and you want faster access, you can

152
00:09:05,222 --> 00:09:06,116
wrap the prompts.

153
00:09:06,441 --> 00:09:08,996
Claude Code has slash commands and skills.

154
00:09:09,321 --> 00:09:11,027
Cursor has commands and rules.

155
00:09:11,074 --> 00:09:12,479
Codex has exec.

156
00:09:12,920 --> 00:09:15,346
But the prompt is the source of truth.

157
00:09:15,787 --> 00:09:18,551
The wrapper is just a convenience layer.

158
00:09:19,551 --> 00:09:22,860
So far everything we've described works within a single repo.

159
00:09:22,895 --> 00:09:27,260
But real systems span multiple repos — an API, an SDK, a

160
00:09:27,353 --> 00:09:29,327
frontend, shared infrastructure.

161
00:09:29,373 --> 00:09:32,531
When Model A is working on a feature that touches the API

162
00:09:32,647 --> 00:09:37,431
and the SDK, it needs to run and test both components together.  This

163
00:09:37,477 --> 00:09:39,103
is what the dev environment solves.

164
00:09:39,219 --> 00:09:40,937
You create a system repo.

165
00:09:41,262 --> 00:09:44,141
The system repo doesn't contain application code.

166
00:09:44,315 --> 00:09:48,286
It describes the system — which repos, how they connect, what contracts

167
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:53,708
they share — and provides a containerised workspace where

168
00:09:53,951 --> 00:09:57,736
Model A can operate on the full system.  The

169
00:09:57,806 --> 00:10:00,813
architecture is containers within a container.

170
00:10:01,254 --> 00:10:03,634
The outer container is the dev environment.

171
00:10:04,017 --> 00:10:09,322
Inside it, each component runs in its own container — the API,

172
00:10:09,671 --> 00:10:14,628
the SDK, the frontend, the database, the cache.

173
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:17,438
Model A works in the outer container.

174
00:10:17,984 --> 00:10:23,951
It can start, stop, restart, and test any component from there.  Component

175
00:10:24,009 --> 00:10:28,456
repos are cloned into a components directory inside the dev environment.

176
00:10:29,152 --> 00:10:33,878
Changes Model A makes to component code are reflected immediately in the

177
00:10:33,913 --> 00:10:36,107
running containers through volume mounts.

178
00:10:36,490 --> 00:10:41,389
Model A edits the API code, restarts the API container, runs the

179
00:10:41,447 --> 00:10:43,223
tests, sees the result.

180
00:10:43,734 --> 00:10:47,310
It can do the same for any component without leaving the workspace.  The

181
00:10:47,356 --> 00:10:50,398
system repo has its own Progressive Disclosure docs.

182
00:10:50,723 --> 00:10:54,438
It publishes a system card — the system-level equivalent of a repo

183
00:10:54,508 --> 00:10:58,954
card — that lists the component repos, the dependency map, and the

184
00:10:58,989 --> 00:11:00,429
shared conventions.

185
00:11:00,940 --> 00:11:05,514
When a change spans multiple components, Model A reads the system card

186
00:11:05,560 --> 00:11:10,333
to understand what's affected, works through the Plan and Implementation cycle for

187
00:11:10,379 --> 00:11:15,476
each component, then runs cross-component tests to verify the contracts still

188
00:11:15,545 --> 00:11:16,811
hold.  This

189
00:11:16,881 --> 00:11:22,105
replaces the older idea of coordinating separate agents across separate

190
00:11:22,152 --> 00:11:24,694
repos via transport layers.

191
00:11:25,135 --> 00:11:30,569
The orchestration problem largely goes away when one agent can see

192
00:11:30,720 --> 00:11:33,994
and run everything in one workspace.

193
00:11:34,994 --> 00:11:38,314
AI DevKit is an operating model, not a tool.

194
00:11:38,373 --> 00:11:39,824
It publishes standards.

195
00:11:40,265 --> 00:11:44,653
The standards define how AI agents work in your repos.  Progressive

196
00:11:44,677 --> 00:11:48,299
Disclosure docs give agents a consistent operating surface.

197
00:11:48,740 --> 00:11:53,152
Specs give work items a structured shape that two models can verify.

198
00:11:53,849 --> 00:11:59,062
Test-driven development with test-author and implementer separation prevents AI from testing

199
00:11:59,108 --> 00:12:00,455
its own assumptions.

200
00:12:01,151 --> 00:12:06,747
Cross-verification between independent training lineages catches errors that self-review misses.

201
00:12:07,072 --> 00:12:10,811
And the whole thing runs on plain markdown — no install, no

202
00:12:10,881 --> 00:12:13,562
plugins, no vendor lock-in.  The

203
00:12:13,609 --> 00:12:16,976
human's job is to make the decisions that matter: approve the spec

204
00:12:17,022 --> 00:12:19,611
at the front, approve the release at the back.

205
00:12:20,215 --> 00:12:25,416
Everything in between is AI execution, verified by a second AI with

206
00:12:25,463 --> 00:12:27,332
different blind spots.  That's

207
00:12:27,448 --> 00:12:28,864
AI DevKit.
